\begin_layout Standard
adverse event: "An adverse event (AE) is any untoward medical occurrence
 in a patient administered a medicinal product and which does not necessarily
 have to have a causal relationship with this treatment.
 An adverse event can therefore be any unfavorable and unintended sign (for
 example, an abnormal laboratory finding), symptom, or disease temporally
 associated with the use of a medicinal product, whether or not considered
 related to this medicinal product."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Development of Vaccines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vaccine research is long, complex and costly.
 Because a vaccine is a biological product made from living microorganisms,
 its development cycle is quite different from that of a pharmaceutical
 product:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exploratory stage: to understand the disease, its epidemiological data and
 the right proteins (antigens) to use in preventing or treating the disease
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pre-clinical stage: to assess antigen safety and select the best candidate
 vaccine 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Clinical development: from 10 (Phase I) to 1,000 people (Phase III) are
 involved in clinical trials and the first batches are produced (clinical
 batches and industrial batches for compliance) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regulatory approval: all the data collected through the preceding stages
 are submitted to the relevant health authorities for approval 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Manufacturing process: takes up to 22 months to produce a single batch of
 vaccine 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Quality control: approximately 70% of production time is dedicated to quality
 control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
为什么有的男生在追女生之前还要问一下对方？（知乎）
