\begin_layout Section
3.2 Install Mosek & Rmosek
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Install Mosek & Rmosek
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I first installed Mosek and set up the PATH in .bashrc so that mosek can
 be called anywhere in terminal by simply typing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mosek
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 But when I turned to install Romosek, R returned the message saying that
 it can't find the 
\emph on
PKG_MOSEKHOME 
\emph default
variable.
 I typed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sys.getenv("LD_LIBRARY_PATH")
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in R and it seems that the path to mosek is not in is not in LD_LIBRARY_PATH.
 Then I searched online for help, then find the following email from the
 Rmosek author Friberg:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color blue
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The ~/.bashrc file is read every time you open a new bash terminal.
 Exported variables affects the entire bash session and typically all its
 subprocesses.
 Unfortunately R is not affected!!
\emph default
\color inherit
 You have at least three ways to fix this so that R can also read the defined
 variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) Copy the definitions to the ~/.Rprofile file.
 This file is read as an R script when you open a R console.
 Variables defined with Sys.setenv will affect the entire R session and typically
 all its subprocesses.
 Use Sys.getenv to get the variable definitions for PATH and LD_LIBRARY_PATH
 so you do not overwrite anything - only append.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) Move the definitions to the ~/.profile file.
 This file is read when you login to the system, except on some systems
 when you login from a bash terminal and the ~/.bash_profile file exists.
 Exported variables affects the entire login session.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) Move the definitions to the ~/.bash_profile file.
 This file is only read when you login to the system from a bash terminal
 (typically through ssh tunneling).
 Exported variables affects the entire login session.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hope you find a solution that works for you.
 You may want to make one file call the other (remember to check if it exists).
 Also, you can use "/etc/profile" or "/etc/environment" instead of "~/.profile"
 if you have root access to the system and want the variables to be defined
 for all users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can read more about this here https://help.ubuntu.com/community/EnvironmentVar
iables#Persistent_environment_variables
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color blue
I found it has some interesting information about the difference between
 .bashrc, .Rprofile, .profile and .bash_profile and I also want to know more
 about how to configure the .Rprofile in the future.

\emph default
\color inherit
 But I didn't try his suggestion for installation but manually installed
 Rmosek by specifying that variable directly using script 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

install.packages("Rmosek", type="source", INSTALL_opts="--no-multiarch",
 repos="http://download.mosek.com/R/7", configure.vars="PKG_MOSEKHOME=/home/sadappl
elc/mosek/7/tools/platform/linux64x86 PKG_MOSEKLIB=mosek64")
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
successfully.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Semicircle and Hemisphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Q:Why is half of a circle called a semi-circle, but half of a sphere called
 a hemisphere?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Answer(by Justin Rising on Quora):"semi" and "hemi" are respectively Latin
 and Greek prefixes meaning "half".
 The word "circle" is of Latin origin, so it gets the Latin prefix, but
 the word "sphere" is of Greek origin, so it gets the Greek prefix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
3.4 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
litigation 诉讼，打官司
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Suspension Training
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field of suspension training is a form of resistance training that includes
 bodyweight exercises in which a variety of multi-planar, compound exercise
 movements can be performed.
 These are done with the aim of developing strength, balance, flexibility,
 and joint stability simultaneously.
 Suspension training develops physical strength while using functional movements
 and dynamic positions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
今日最佳段子
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Q:北大的同学凌晨四点半真的在看书吗？
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
