\begin_layout Section
9.16 org mode notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Org mode notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
A timestamp is a specification of a date (possibly with a time or a range
 of times) in a special format
\emph default
, either ‘<2003-09-16 Tue>’1 or ‘<2003-09-16 Tue 09:39>’ or ‘<2003-09-16
 Tue 12:00-12:30>’2.
 A timestamp
\color blue
 can appear anywhere in the headline or body of an Org tree entry
\color inherit
.
 Its presence causes entries to be shown on specific dates in the agenda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For more complex date specifications, Org mode supports using the 
\emph on
\color blue
special sexp diary entries
\emph default
\color inherit
 implemented in the Emacs calendar/diary package3.
 For example with optional time: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
<%%(diary-float t 4 2)>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two timestamps connected by ‘--’ denote a range.
 The headline will be shown on the first and last day of the range, and
 on any dates that are displayed and fall in the range.
 Here is an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
<2004-08-23 Mon>--<2004-08-26 Thu>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inactive timestamp: Just like a plain timestamp, 
\emph on
\color blue
but with square brackets instead of angular ones
\emph default
\color inherit
.
 These timestamps are inactive in the sense that they do not trigger an
 entry to show up in the agenda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Creating timestamp
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c .
 (org-time-stamp) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c ! (org-time-stamp-inactive)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color blue
Note: to use the alternative format which contains date and time, add C-u
 to the previous two 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c < (org-date-from-calendar)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c > (org-goto-calendar)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-o (org-open-at-point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-<left> (org-timestamp-down-day) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-<right> (org-timestamp-up-day)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-<up> (org-timestamp-up) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-<down> (org-timestamp-down-down)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note: 
\emph on
\color blue
the previous two commands change the item under the cursor in a timestamp
\emph default
\color inherit
.
 The cursor can be on a year, month, day, hour or minute.
 When the timestamp contains a time range like ‘15:30-16:30’, modifying
 the first time will also shift the second, shifting the time block with
 constant length.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-y (org-evaluate-time-range)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note: The above command evaluate a time range by computing the difference
 between start and end.
 With a prefix argument, insert result after the time range (in a table:
 into the following column).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Date/Time prompt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Org mode accepts date/time information in a variety of formats.
 Assume that today is June 13, 2006, we have the following egs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3-2-5 ⇒ 2003-02-05 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2/5/3 ⇒ 2003-02-05 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color blue
14 ⇒ 2006-06-14 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color blue
12 ⇒ 2006-07-12 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2/5 ⇒ 2007-02-05 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461675

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fri ⇒ nearest Friday after the default date 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461679

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
sep 15 ⇒ 2006-09-15 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461684

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
feb 15 ⇒ 2007-02-15 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461689

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
sep 12 9 ⇒ 2009-09-12 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461700

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
12:45 ⇒ 2006-06-13
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461704

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
12:45 22 sept 0:34 ⇒ 2006-09-22 00:34 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461711

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
w4 ⇒ ISO week for of the current year 2006 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461732

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2012 w4 fri ⇒ Friday of ISO week 4 in 2012
\change_deleted -954680643 1442461759
 
\change_inserted -954680643 1442461757

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore you can specify a relative date by giving, as the first thing
 in the input: a plus/minus sign, a number and a letter ([hdwmy]) to indicate
 change in hours, days, weeks, months, or years.
 
\emph on
\color red
With a single plus or minus, the date is always relative to today.
 With a double plus or minus, it is relative to the default date.
 If instead of a single letter, you use the abbreviation of day name, the
 date will be the Nth such day
\emph default
\color inherit
, e.g.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
+0 ⇒ today 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
.
 ⇒ today 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
+4d ⇒ four days from today
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
+4 ⇒ same as above 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
+2w ⇒ two weeks from today 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
++5 ⇒ five days from default date 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
+2tue ⇒ second Tuesday from now
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
-wed ⇒ last Wednesday
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can specify a time range by giving start and end times or by giving
 a start time and a duration (in HH:MM format).
 Use one or two dash(es) as the separator in the former case and use '+'
 as the separator in the latter case, e.g.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
11am-1:15pm ⇒ 11:00-13:15 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
11am--1:15pm ⇒ same as above 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
11am+2:15 ⇒ same as above
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To control the calendar fully 
\emph on
\color red
from the minibuffer
\emph default
\color inherit
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
<RET> Choose date at cursor in calendar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
mouse-1 Select date by clicking on it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-<right>/<left> One day forward/backward.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
S-<down>/<up> One week forward/backward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
M-S-<right>/<left> One month forward/backward.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
> / < Scroll calendar forward/backward by one month.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
M-v / C-v Scroll calendar forward/backward by 3 months.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
M-S-<down>/<up> Scroll calendar forward/backward by one year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Deadlines and scheduling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
You can specify a different lead time for warnings for a specific deadline
 using the following syntax.

\color inherit
 Here is an example with a warning period of 5 days DEADLINE: 
\emph on
\color red
<2004-02-29 Sun -5d>
\emph default
\color inherit
.
 This warning is deactivated if the task gets scheduled and you set org-agenda-s
kip-deadline-prewarning-if-scheduled to t.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
Meaning of Scheduling in Org Mode
\color inherit
: setting a date when you want to start working on an action item
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The headline will be listed under the given date1.
 In addition, a reminder that the scheduled date has passed will be present
 in the compilation for today, until the entry is marked DONE, i.e., the task
 will automatically be forwarded until completed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you want to delay the display of this task in the agenda, use SCHEDULED:
 
\color blue
<2004-12-25 Sat -2d>
\color inherit
: the task is still scheduled on the 25th but will appear two days later.
 In case the task contains a repeater, the delay is considered to affect
 all occurrences; if you want the delay to only affect the first scheduled
 occurrence of the task, use --2d instead.
 See org-scheduled-delay-days and org-agenda-skip-scheduled-delay-if-deadline
 for details on how to control this globally or per agenda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-d (org-deadline) When called with a prefix arg, an existing deadline
 will be removed from the entry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-s (org-schedule) When called with a prefix argument, remove the scheduling
 date from the entry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color blue
C-c / d (org-check-deadlines)
\color inherit
 : Create a sparse tree with all deadlines that are either past-due, or
 which will become due within org-deadline-warning-days.
 With C-u prefix, show all deadlines in the file.
 With a numeric prefix, check that many days.
 For example, C-1 C-c / d shows all deadlines due tomorrow.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c / b (org-check-before-date) : Sparse tree for deadlines and scheduled
 items before a given date.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c / a (org-check-after-date)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that org-schedule and org-deadline supports setting the date by indicating
 a relative time: e.g., +1d will set the date to the next day after today,
 and –1w will set the date to the previous week before any current timestamp.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Repeated tasks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some tasks need to be repeated again and again.
 Org mode helps to organize such tasks using a so-called repeater in a DEADLINE,
 SCHEDULED, or plain timestamp.
 In the following example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
** TODO Pay the rent DEADLINE: <2005-10-01 Sat +1m>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the +1m is a repeater; the intended interpretation is that the task has
 a deadline on <2005-10-01> and repeats itself every (one) month starting
 from that time.
 You can use yearly, monthly, weekly, daily and hourly repeat cookies by
 using the 
\emph on
\color blue
y/w/m/d/h
\emph default
\color inherit
 letters.
 
\emph on
If you need both a repeater and a special warning period in a deadline entry,
 the repeater should come first and the warning period last
\emph default
: DEADLINE: 
\color blue
<2005-10-01 Sat +1m -3d>
\color inherit
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deadlines and scheduled items produce entries in the agenda when they are
 over-due, so it is important to be able to mark such an entry as completed
 once you have done so.
 When you mark a DEADLINE or a SCHEDULE with the TODO keyword DONE, it will
 no longer produce entries in the agenda.
 The problem with this is, however, that then also the next instance of
 the repeated entry will not be active.

\emph on
\color blue
 Org mode deals with this in the following way: When you try to mark such
 an entry DONE (using C-c C-t), it will shift the base date of the repeating
 timestamp by the repeater interval, and immediately set the entry state
 back to TODO
\emph default
\color inherit
.
 In the example above, setting the state to DONE would actually switch the
 date like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
** TODO Pay the rent DEADLINE: <2005-11-01 Tue +1m>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color blue
To mark a task with a repeater as DONE, use C-- 1 C-c C-t (i.e., org-todo
 with a numeric prefix argument of -1.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A timestamp will be added under the deadline, to keep a record that you
 actually acted on the previous instance of this deadline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a consequence of shifting the base date, 
\emph on
this entry will no longer be visible in the agenda when checking past dates,
 but all future instances will be visible
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Org mode has special repeaters 
\color blue
‘++’
\color inherit
 and 
\color blue
‘.+’
\color inherit
.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
** TODO Call Father DEADLINE: <2008-02-10 Sun ++1w> 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marking this DONE will shift the date by at least one week, but also by
 as many weeks as it takes to get this date into the future.
 However, it stays on a Sunday, even if you called and marked it done on
 Saturday.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
** TODO Check the batteries in the smoke detectors DEADLINE: <2005-11-01
 Tue .+1m> 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marking this DONE will shift the date to one month after today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You may have both scheduling and deadline information for a specific task.
 If the repeater is set for the scheduling information only, you probably
 want the repeater to be ignored after the deadline.
 If so, set the variable 
\color blue
org-agenda-skip-scheduled-if-deadline-is-shown
\color inherit
 to repeated-after-deadline.
 If you want both scheduling and deadline information to repeat after the
 same interval, set the same repeater for both timestamps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative to using a repeater is to create a number of copies of a
 task subtree, with dates shifted in each copy.
 The command C-c C-x c was created for this purpose, it is described in
 
\emph on
\color blue
Structure editing
\emph default
\color inherit
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Clocking work time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Org mode allows you to clock the time you spend on specific tasks in a project.
 When you start working on an item, you can start the clock.
 When you stop working on that task, or when you mark the task done, the
 clock is stopped and the corresponding time interval is recorded.
 It also computes the total time spent on each subtree of a project.
 And it remembers a history or tasks recently clocked, so that you can jump
 quickly between a number of tasks absorbing your time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To save the clock history across Emacs sessions, use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
(setq org-clock-persist 'history) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
(org-clock-persistence-insinuate)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you clock into a new task after resuming Emacs, the incomplete clock
 will be found (see Resolving idle time) and you will be prompted about
 what to do with it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x C-i (org-clock-in)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x C-o (org-clock-out) Stop the clock (clock-out).
 This inserts another timestamp at the same location where the clock was
 last started.
 It also directly computes the resulting time and inserts it after the time
 range as ‘=> HH:MM’.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x C-x (org-clock-in-last) Reclock the last clocked task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x C-e (org-clock-modify-effort-estimate) Update the effort estimate
 for the current clock task.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-c or C-c C-y (org-evaluate-time-range) Recompute the time interval
 after changing one of the timestamps.
 This is only necessary if you edit the timestamps directly.
 If you change them with S-<cursor> keys, the update is automatic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x C-q (org-clock-cancel) 
\emph on
\color blue
Cancel the current clock
\emph default
\color inherit
.
 This is useful if a clock was started by mistake, or if you ended up working
 on something else.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x C-d (org-clock-display) 
\color blue
Display time summaries for each subtree in the current buffer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The clock table & Effort estimates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be study in the future
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Taking notes with a timer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x 0 (org-timer-start) Start or reset the relative timer.
 By default, the timer is set to 0.
 When called with a C-u prefix, prompt the user for a starting offset.
 If there is a timer string at point, this is taken as the default, providing
 a convenient way to restart taking notes after a break in the process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x ; (org-timer-set-timer) Start a countdown timer.
 The user is prompted for a duration.
 org-timer-default-timer sets the default countdown value.
 Giving a prefix numeric argument overrides this default value.
 This command is available as ; in agenda buffers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x .
 (org-timer) Insert the value of the current relative or countdown timer
 into the buffer.
 If no timer is running, the relative timer will be started.
 When called with a prefix argument, the relative timer is restarted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x - (org-timer-item) Insert a description list item with the value
 of the current relative or countdown timer.
 With a prefix argument, first reset the relative timer to 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x 
\backslash
 (org-timer-pause-or-continue) Pause the timer, or continue it if it is
 already paused.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
C-c C-x _ (org-timer-stop) Stop the timer.
 After this, you can only start a new timer, not continue the old one.
 This command also removes the timer from the mode line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
9.18 Revisit Xiaochuan Liu's Blog
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
一些近况（刘小川）
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
好久没有更新博客，觉得没什么可说的，偶尔写出来一些短文也感觉质量不高。有时候心里有一些话，觉得很适合写在博客里面，可是过了几个星期就被正事儿挤的没时间写了。另一
方面，我在学术方面的一些东西，随手写的一些笔记又零散又混乱，不太觉得有太多意义。再加上疏懒，也没有贴出来什么。头几年我在南开大学期间，没有太多机会和真正做学术的
人交流，当时写写博客，自娱自乐。我如今反而觉得那时候写的一些东西其实也挺无聊的，不过那都的确是我当时的真实想法，我依然觉得也许对某些人有意义。所以我不打算删除任
何一篇。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
这多半年其实在我身边，在IMPA，还是发生了不少事情的。比如，我的导师Artur Avila，获2014年菲尔兹奖。7，8月份的时候，IMPA铺天盖地的宣传，搞
的我也有一些莫名的压力。人人都来问我一些跟Artur有关的问题，而我自己才刚刚开始做科研，这初入的门槛并不好迈。想成为一两个方向的专家，路还相当的遥远。我只是能
说，Avila其人永远是工作的状态，他在学术上正教我很多东西，我相信他今后能给我带来更多的影响。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
这几个月时间里，我也有机会认识了一些朋友，知道了一些在认认真真在做数学的同行。我在出国了以后才知道了更多国内认真做事儿的人，这真是一个讽刺。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
真正在静下心思做数学研究的人，无论他暂时已经出来的成果怎样，我们都有一个共同的值得骄傲的地方：我们每一天都在面对失败。我通过博士资格考试之后的一年时间里，稍微回
顾过去，满纸写着的都是失败失败和失败。百折不挠就是我们做数学的人的座右铭。习惯这样的生活肯定是必要的。
\emph default
没有任何一个数学工作者，哪怕他是一位著名的大人物，敢张嘴就说，他打算明天一早上起来，去解决一个什么什么猜想。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
我仍然有时候会回想自己在国内某个研究所的生活。那里面所有人都在玩政治，要么属于胆小如鼠型的，要么则自己偷偷想办法跑出去，当然，谁也不能告诉谁。某些导师呢，他们什
么都不做，学生要排着队把写好的论文呈上伺候着。那时候我可以说见到了某种极端，某种最坏的科研环境。一堆不做科研的很无知的人很专制的去压制年轻的生命。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
还好我已经远离了这些破事儿。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color red
近几个月，我更多的却看到了一些很差劲的中国学生的例子。有些人一开始摆出一个热爱数学的样子给别人看，几个月都坚持不下去，就被其他更加光鲜的什么东西吸引跑了，这些人
短期抱着的是旅游的心态，长期怀着买彩票的心态，自然在浪费青春。“投机”两个大字，刻在他们的脸上。可是做科研不由得你投机。你自己的人生，到底想做什么，请花一点儿时
间坐下来为自己想清楚，然后你再跟别人交流。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
我一开始对这类人容忍度很低，突然有一天我想明白一件事，原来我在国内外碰见的这两类中国人其实是一类人。无非就是这后一类人当中偶尔有一些顺利的，稀里糊涂的捡到很多便
宜，再包装的漂漂亮亮的回国去，他们根本自始自终也不知道自己要干什么，我是做软件呢？还是做学术？开一个公司做几年，倒闭了也没关系。哦，原来当官最“好”，那就去买个
官当当，在政治舞台上表演表演。当然，在学术界还得继续摆出个学者的模样，八面玲珑，各取所需。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
看清楚这些，我也多了一些容忍，这样的人我如今也容易辨认。辨认出来之后，Ignore就是最有力，最简单的武器。我早已看到了这类人将来的两个方向，无论是哪一个，都是
我不愿接触的。每个人选择自己的人生，每个人自己需要去承担后果，如此而已。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
小学生英语教学（刘小川）
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
本文探讨10岁以下儿童的教育，以学习英语为主要的内容。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
我表妹还有一个月时间就到9岁。从今年9月中旬开始，我和我的夫人测试了一下我的表妹的英语能力，结果是，她的水平大约在新概念第一册的72课左右。这个测试结果是令人难
以置信的，因为她所在的学校已经教了她超过三年的英语。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
我自己的看法是，如果这样教，那么不如不教。孩子如果认为自己还没学过英语，也要远远比这样自己感觉学过三年，其实基本上仅仅学会了2，3个月的程度要好得多。她所得到的
英文的知识非常混乱和盲目。我特别惊讶的发现，学校基本上对所有学科的教育都是这个风格。比如数学，已经4年级的孩子，居然被领着每天“认识更大的数”。最近几年小学弱化
正式教育，搞一些所谓的“减轻负担”的形式主义的活动。这样子很可能会让不少小孩子成为牺牲品。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
家庭一定要在孩子的教育中起到作用。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
为了这个目的，我们已经在过去几个月很辛苦的寻找一些合适的校外教育途径。我们试着找了很多各类家教或者课外辅导的教学。我再一次十分的失望。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
课外其实有不少所谓的外语学校，规模大小不一。有的还指出是特别为10岁以下小朋友开设的。经过半年左右的接触，我发现授课教师普遍视野极其短浅，他们唯一能看到的就是下
一个教育阶段，也就是说，所谓“考上某些初中”，是他们眼睛里唯一的目的。对于英语学习这个整体，可以说他们是不合格的教师，我怀疑他们自己也从不了解学英文到底要达到一
个什么目的，就敢出来教书了。这样的直接后果就是，他们没办法突出重点，而且她们普遍很不虚心，自以为是，难以沟通。他们不知道孩子后面继续要怎样学习，稀里糊涂，以挣钱
为唯一目的，教和学的效率都十分低下。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
我自己也是经历了很多不合格的老师，自己学英文也遇到过波折。我如今开始插手改变这样一种弱智的教育现状。仅仅从9月中旬开始，我请到家中一名家庭教师。至今在接近一个月
的教学中，我的表妹开始从新概念第1册的第73课程开始，现在大约学到90课左右。由于她对于很基本的句法结构一丁点儿都不了解，音标完全没学过。一开始的学习进度并不是
很快。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
在新概念的第一册70到90课的地方，教材已经开始强调一些情态动词以及动词“have”的不同用法，逐渐介绍完成时态。初学者一般对完成时态和过去时态的区别分不清楚，
这是因为中文没有相应的语言现象。小孩子接受的其实很快，比我预想的更容易，她们没有任何学习负担，只需要每天投入3，4个小时，就很愉快的按部就班的往下进行。她们往往
只需要一个好老师而已。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
可是10月1日这么个节日，又耽误了不少的事儿。在中国一到过节的时候，过节每个人都不由得自己，全部被一些莫名其妙的人和事儿给牵着鼻子走。我对很多陋习非常反感。总之
我不得不把这5，6天从表妹的学习计划表中划掉。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color red
想要完成一件事情，是需要很多牺牲的。这常常不是每个人都明白的。很多人一会儿要这样，一会儿又想那样，于是一年变化三百六十个目标，终究一事无成。
\emph default
\color inherit
我的一些以前的同学总是说，“我也想把英语重新捡起来。”于是他们偶尔会像模像样的学几个小时，还没坚持到学到新东西呢，仅仅是复习了那么点儿早就知道的东西，就一定会遇
到一大堆麻烦，要不然就是交通太拥挤了天气不好；要不然就是好久没联系的亲戚朋友来了，一定得一起吃一顿。反正哪一件事情都比坚持学习更重要，于是放弃掉不再做了。其实，
上面的这些事情都没有想象中那么重要，无非是自己懒惰给自己找的借口。等到下次心血来潮的时候，往往都是几年以后了。这些够成了成年人拖延的基本原因。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\color red
问题是，很多人都不在自己身上找原因。影响到下一代的教育，让他们从来都不知道该怎样完成一件事。孩子其实一开始并没有这么多毛病，往往也是成年人把孩子“教坏了”。对任
何一件事情，如果真的决定要做，就一定要坚持到多少有点儿成效才能休息，不然就不如不做。绝大多数孩子从一开始并不知道所谓“熬时间”，“混时间”的意义，他们根本不会这
么做。他们在跟成年人的接触中发现了这么做的好处，因为不需要真的“学会”，只要把时间混到位，家长就会让他们去玩，吃吃喝喝。
\emph default
\color inherit
从很多角度来看，成年人是在这场战役当中败给孩子了。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
我打算把我的表妹于今年年底12月带到里约一个月，尽自己最大的努力帮她建立合理有效的学习习惯。这次一个月的试验，我打算以教英文为主要的内容，辅助以阅读和几部电影欣
赏。如果还有多余的时间，我也考虑教她一点儿数学。但是如果我不满意的话，她会在里约得不到去海滩的机会，只能关在家门里整整一个月，在这一点上我们必须说到做到，不然又
给了小孩儿看到了机会，前功尽弃。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
在剩下2个月左右的准备时间里，我的要求是她必须基本上完成新概念第1册全部内容。我将会在她来之后从第二册开始教起，我会找一个母语英语的朋友和我一起间隔给她讲授。我
目前在起草这一个月的课程安排。我十分重视这次试验。
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
